[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] The **`IDBDatabase`** interface of the IndexedDB API provides a connection to a database; you can use an `IDBDatabase` object to open a transaction on your database then create, manipulate, and delete objects (data) in that database.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] The interface provides the only way to get and manage versions of the database.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] A string that contains the name of the connected database.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] A 64-bit integer that contains the version of the connected database.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] When a database is first created, this attribute is an empty string.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] A `DOMStringList` that contains a list of the names of the object stores currently in the connected database.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] Returns immediately and closes the connection to a database in a separate thread.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] Creates and returns a new object store or index.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] Destroys the object store with the given name in the connected database, along with any indexes that reference it.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] Immediately returns a transaction object (`IDBTransaction`) containing the `IDBTransaction.objectStore` method, which you can use to access your object store.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] An event fired when the database connection is unexpectedly closed.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] An event fired when a database structure change was requested.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] An event fired when a transaction is aborted.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] An event fired when a request returns an error and the event bubbles up to the connection object.
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] In the following code snippet, we open a database asynchronously (`IDBFactory`), handle success and error cases, and create a new object store in the case that an upgrade is needed (`IDBDatabase`).
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] For a complete working example, see our To-do Notifications app (view example live).
[src:indexeddb/api-idbdatabase] This next line opens up a transaction on the Database, then opens an object store that we can then manipulate the data inside of.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] The **`IDBObjectStore`** interface of the IndexedDB API represents an object store in a database.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Records within an object store are sorted according to their keys.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] This sorting enables fast insertion, look-up, and ordered retrieval.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] A list of the names of indexes on objects in this object store.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] If this attribute is `null`, the application must provide a key for each modification operation.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] The `IDBTransaction` object to which this object store belongs.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] The value of the auto increment flag for this object store.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Returns an `IDBRequest` object and, in a separate thread, creates a structured clone of the `value`, and stores the cloned value in the object store.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] This is for adding new records to an object store.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Creates and immediately returns an `IDBRequest` object, and clears this object store in a separate thread.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] This is for deleting all current records out of an object store.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Returns an `IDBRequest` object and, in a separate thread, returns the total number of records that match the provided key or `IDBKeyRange`.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] If no arguments are provided, it returns the total number of records in the store.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Creates a new index during a version upgrade, returning a new `IDBIndex` object in the connected database.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] returns an `IDBRequest` object and, in a separate thread, deletes the store object selected by the specified key.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] This is for deleting individual records out of an object store.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Destroys the specified index in the connected database, used during a version upgrade.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Returns an `IDBRequest` object and, in a separate thread, returns the store object store selected by the specified key.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] This is for retrieving specific records from an object store.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Returns an `IDBRequest` object and, in a separate thread, retrieves and returns the record key for the object in the object stored matching the specified parameter.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Returns an `IDBRequest` object and, in a separate thread, retrieves all objects in the object store matching the specified parameter or all objects in the store if no parameters are given.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Returns an `IDBRequest` object and, in a separate thread, retrieves record keys for all objects in the object store matching the specified parameter or all objects in the store if no parameters are given.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Returns an `IDBRequest` object and, in a separate thread, finds all matching records in the object store (including primary keys and values) that correspond to the given key or are in range, if `key` is an `IDBKeyRange`.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Opens an index from this object store after which it can, for example, be used to return a sequence of records sorted by that index using a cursor.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Returns an `IDBRequest` object and, in a separate thread, returns a new `IDBCursorWithValue` object.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Used for iterating through an object store by primary key with a cursor.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Returns an `IDBRequest` object and, in a separate thread, returns a new `IDBCursor`.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] Used for iterating through an object store with a key.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] This is for updating existing records in an object store when the transaction's mode is `readwrite`.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] This example shows a variety of different uses of object stores, from updating the data structure with `IDBObjectStore.createIndex` inside an `onupgradeneeded` function, to adding a new item to our object store with `IDBObjectStore.add`.
[src:indexeddb/idbobjectstore] For a full working example, see our To-do Notifications app (view example live).
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] The **`IDBTransaction`** interface of the IndexedDB API provides a static, asynchronous transaction on a database using event handler attributes.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] All reading and writing of data is done within transactions.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] You use `IDBDatabase` to start transactions, `IDBTransaction` to set the mode of the transaction (e.g., is it `readonly` or `readwrite`), and you access an `IDBObjectStore` to make a request.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] You can also use an `IDBTransaction` object to abort transactions.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] After the code is executed the object store should contain the value "2", since `trans2` should run after `trans1`.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] A transaction alternates between *active* and *inactive* states between event loop tasks.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] It's active in the task when it was created, and in each task of the requests' `success` or `error` event handlers.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] It's inactive in all other tasks, in which case placing requests will fail.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] If no new requests are placed when the transaction is active, and there are no other outstanding requests, the transaction will automatically commit.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Note that as of Firefox 40, IndexedDB transactions have relaxed durability guarantees to increase performance (see Firefox bug 1112702.) Previously in a `readwrite` transaction, a `complete` event was fired only when all data was guaranteed to have been flushed to disk.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] In Firefox 40+ the `complete` event is fired after the OS has been told to write the data but potentially before that data has actually been flushed to disk.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] The `complete` event may thus be delivered quicker than before, however, there exists a small chance that the entire transaction will be lost if the OS crashes or there is a loss of system power before the data is flushed to disk.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Since such catastrophic events are rare, most consumers should not need to concern themselves further.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] The database connection with which this transaction is associated.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Returns the durability hint the transaction was created with.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Returns a `DOMException` indicating the type of error that occurred when there is an unsuccessful transaction.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] This property is `null` if the transaction is not finished, is finished and successfully committed, or was aborted with the `IDBTransaction.abort()` function.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] The mode for isolating access to data in the object stores that are in the scope of the transaction.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Returns a `DOMStringList` of the names of `IDBObjectStore` objects associated with the transaction.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Rolls back all the changes to objects in the database associated with this transaction.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] If this transaction has been aborted or completed, this method fires an error event.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Returns an `IDBObjectStore` object representing an object store that is part of the scope of this transaction.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] For an active transaction, commits the transaction.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Note that this doesn't normally *have* to be called — a transaction will automatically commit when all outstanding requests have been satisfied and no new requests have been made.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] `commit()` can be used to start the commit process without waiting for events from outstanding requests to be dispatched.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] An event fired when the `IndexedDB` transaction is aborted.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Also available via the `onabort` property; this event bubbles to `IDBDatabase`.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] An event fired when the transaction successfully completes.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Also available via the `oncomplete` property.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] An event fired when a request returns an error and the event bubbles up to the connection object (`IDBDatabase`).
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Also available via the `onerror` property.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Even if these constants are now deprecated, you can still use them to provide backward compatibility if required.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] In the following code snippet, we open a read/write transaction on our database and add some data to an object store.
[src:indexeddb/idbtransaction] Note also the functions attached to transaction event handlers to report on the outcome of the transaction opening in the event of success or failure.
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] The **Indexed Database API** (commonly referred to as **IndexedDB**) is a JavaScript application programming interface (API) provided by web browsers for managing a NoSQL database of objects.
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] It is a standard maintained by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C).
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] As an alternative to the Web storage standard, IndexedDB can provide more storage capacity.
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] Web storage has fixed limits per website, but IndexedDB limits are "usually quite large, if they exist at all".
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] Use cases for IndexedDB include caching web application data for offline availability.
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] Some browser modules, such as devtools or extensions, may also use it for storage.
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] Support for IndexedDB was added to Firefox version 4 (March 2011), Google Chrome version 11, Internet Explorer version 10, Safari version 8, and Microsoft Edge version 12.
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] Web SQL Database was a prior API developed by Apple.
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] But Firefox refused to add support for it and argued against it becoming a standard because it would codify the quirks of SQLite.
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] WebSQL was deprecated in favor of IndexedDB.
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] Because IndexedDB is running inside of the security sandbox of a browser, all operations have to go through various security layers which decreases the performance of IndexedDB.
[src:indexeddb/indexed-database-api] With IndexedDB 2.0 the getAll() method was added which allows to improve performance on bulk read operations.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] IndexedDB is a low-level API for client-side storage of significant amounts of structured data, including files/blobs.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] This API uses indexes to enable high-performance searches of this data.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] While Web Storage is useful for storing smaller amounts of data, it is less useful for storing larger amounts of structured data.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] This is the main landing page for MDN's IndexedDB coverage — here we provide links to the full API reference and usage guides, browser support details, and some explanation of key concepts.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] IndexedDB is a transactional database system, like an SQL-based Relational Database Management System (RDBMS).
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] However, unlike SQL-based RDBMSes, which use fixed-column tables, IndexedDB is a JavaScript-based object-oriented database.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] IndexedDB lets you store and retrieve objects that are indexed with a **key**; any objects supported by the structured clone algorithm can be stored.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] You need to specify the database schema, open a connection to your database, and then retrieve and update data within a series of **transactions**.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] Operations performed using IndexedDB are done asynchronously, so as not to block applications.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] There are a number of web technologies that store data of one kind or another on the client side (i.e., on your local disk).
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] IndexedDB is most commonly talked about.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] The process by which the browser works out how much space to allocate to web data storage and what to delete when that limit is reached is not simple, and differs between browsers.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] Browser storage quotas and eviction criteria attempts to explain how this works, at least in the case of Firefox.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] To get access to a database, call `open()` on the `indexedDB` property of a window object.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] This method returns an `IDBRequest` object; asynchronous operations communicate to the calling application by firing events on `IDBRequest` objects.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] An object of this type is the value of the global `Window.indexedDB` and `WorkerGlobalScope.indexedDB` properties.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] It is therefore the entry point for the API.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] Represents a request to open a database.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] It's the only way to get a transaction on the database.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] You create a transaction on a database, specify the scope (such as which object stores you want to access), and determine the kind of access (read only or readwrite) that you want.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] Generic interface that handles database requests and provides access to results.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] Represents an object store that allows access to a set of data in an IndexedDB database, looked up via primary key.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] Also allows access to a subset of data in an IndexedDB database, but uses an index to retrieve the record(s) rather than the primary key.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] This is sometimes faster than using `IDBObjectStore`.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] Iterates over object stores and indexes.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] Iterates over object stores and indexes and returns the cursor's current value.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] Defines a key range that can be used to retrieve data from a database in a certain range.
[src:indexeddb/indexeddb-api] The `IDBVersionChangeEvent` interface indicates that the version of the database has changed, as the result of an `IDBOpenDBRequest.onupgradeneeded` event handler function.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] IndexedDB is a way for you to persistently store data inside a user's browser.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Because it lets you create web applications with rich query abilities regardless of network availability, your applications can work both online and offline.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] This tutorial walks you through using the asynchronous API of IndexedDB.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you are not familiar with IndexedDB, you should first read the IndexedDB key characteristics and basic terminology article.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] For the reference documentation on the IndexedDB API, see the IndexedDB API article and its subpages.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] This article documents the types of objects used by IndexedDB, as well as the methods of the asynchronous API (the synchronous API was removed from spec).
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Start a transaction and make a request to do some database operation, like adding or retrieving data.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Wait for the operation to complete by listening to the right kind of DOM event.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Do something with the results (which can be found on the request object).
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] With these big concepts under our belts, we can get to more concrete stuff.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Opening a database is just like any other operation — you have to "request" it.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The open request doesn't open the database or start the transaction right away.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The call to the `open()` function returns an `IDBOpenDBRequest` object with a result (success) or error value that you handle as an event.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Most other asynchronous functions in IndexedDB do the same thing - return an `IDBRequest` object with the result or error.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The result for the open function is an instance of an `IDBDatabase`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The second parameter to the open method is the version of the database.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The version of the database determines the database schema — the object stores in the database and their structure.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If the database doesn't already exist, it is created by the `open` operation, then an `onupgradeneeded` event is triggered and you create the database schema in the handler for this event.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If the database does exist but you are specifying an upgraded version number, an `onupgradeneeded` event is triggered straight away, allowing you to provide an updated schema in its handler.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] More on this later in Creating or updating the version of the database below, and the `IDBFactory.open` reference page.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If the request succeeds, the `success` event is fired, and the function assigned to `onsuccess` is called.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If the request fails, the `error` event is fired, and the function assigned to `onerror` is called.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The IndexedDB API is designed to minimize the need for error handling, so you're not likely to see many error events (at least, not once you're used to the API!).
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] In the case of opening a database, however, there are some common conditions that generate error events.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The most likely problem is that the user decided not to give your web app permission to create a database.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] One of the main design goals of IndexedDB is to allow large amounts of data to be stored for offline use.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Obviously, browsers do not want to allow some advertising network or malicious website to pollute your computer, so browsers used to prompt the user the first time any given web app attempts to open an IndexedDB for storage.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The user could choose to allow or deny access.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Also, IndexedDB storage in browsers' privacy modes only lasts in-memory until the incognito session is closed.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Now, assuming that the user allowed your request to create a database, and you've received a success event to trigger the success callback; What's next?
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The request here was generated with a call to `indexedDB.open()`, so `request.result` is an instance of `IDBDatabase`, and you definitely want to save that for later.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] As mentioned above, error events bubble.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Error events are targeted at the request that generated the error, then the event bubbles to the transaction, and then finally to the database object.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] One of the common possible errors when opening a database is `VER_ERR`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] It indicates that the version of the database stored on the disk is *greater* than the version that you are trying to open.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] This is an error case that must always be handled by the error handler.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] In this case, the database will already have the object stores from the previous version of the database, so you do not have to create these object stores again.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] You only need to create any new object stores, or delete object stores from the previous version that are no longer needed.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you need to change an existing object store (e.g., to change the `keyPath`), then you must delete the old object store and create it again with the new options.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] (Note that this will delete the information in the object store!
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Trying to create an object store with a name that already exists (or trying to delete an object store with a name that does not already exist) will throw an error.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If the `onupgradeneeded` event exits successfully, the `onsuccess` handler of the open database request will then be triggered.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] IndexedDB uses object stores rather than tables, and a single database can contain any number of object stores.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Whenever a value is stored in an object store, it is associated with a key.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] There are several different ways that a key can be supplied depending on whether the object store uses a key path or a key generator.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] You can also create indices on any object store, provided the object store holds objects, not primitives.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] An index lets you look up the values stored in an object store using the value of a property of the stored object, rather than the object's key.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Additionally, indexes have the ability to enforce simple constraints on the stored data.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] By setting the unique flag when creating the index, the index ensures that no two objects are stored with both having the same value for the index's key path.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] So, for example, if you have an object store which holds a set of people, and you want to ensure that no two people have the same email address, you can use an index with the unique flag set to enforce this.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] That may sound confusing, but this simple example should illustrate the concepts.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Of course, you wouldn't use someone's social security number as the primary key to a customer table because not everyone has a social security number, and you would store their birth date instead of their age, but let's ignore those unfortunate choices for the sake of convenience and move along.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] As indicated previously, `onupgradeneeded` is the only place where you can alter the structure of the database.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] In it, you can create and delete object stores and build and remove indices.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Object stores are created with a single call to `createObjectStore()`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The method takes a name of the store, and a parameter object.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Even though the parameter object is optional, it is very important, because it lets you define important optional properties and refine the type of object store you want to create.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] In our case, we've asked for an object store named "customers" and defined a `keyPath`, which is the property that makes an individual object in the store unique.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] That property in this example is "ssn" since a social security number is guaranteed to be unique.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] "ssn" must be present on every object that is stored in the `objectStore`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] We've also asked for an index named "name" that looks at the `name` property of the stored objects.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] As with `createObjectStore()`, `createIndex()` takes an optional `options` object that refines the type of index that you want to create.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Adding objects that don't have a `name` property still succeeds, but the objects won't appear in the "name" index.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] We can now retrieve the stored customer objects using their `ssn` from the object store directly, or using their name by using the index.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] To learn how this is done, see the section on using an index.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Setting up an `autoIncrement` flag when creating the object store would enable the key generator for that object store.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] With the key generator, the key would be generated automatically as you add the value to the object store.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The current number of a key generator is always set to 1 when the object store for that key generator is first created.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Basically the newly auto-generated key is increased by 1 based on the previous key.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The current number for a key generator never decreases, other than as a result of database operations being reverted, for example, the database transaction is aborted.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Therefore deleting a record or even clearing all records from an object store never affects the object store's key generator.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] For more details about the key generator, see Key generators in the spec.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Before you can do anything with your new database, you need to start a transaction.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Transactions come from the database object, and you have to specify which object stores you want the transaction to span.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Once you are inside the transaction, you can access the object stores that hold your data and make your requests.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Next, you need to decide if you're going to make changes to the database or if you just need to read from it.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Transactions have three available modes: `readonly`, `readwrite`, and `versionchange`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] To change the "schema" or structure of the database—which involves creating or deleting object stores or indexes—the transaction must be in `versionchange` mode.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] This transaction is opened by calling the `IDBFactory.open` method with a `version` specified.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] To read the records of an existing object store, the transaction can either be in `readonly` or `readwrite` mode.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] To make changes to an existing object store, the transaction must be in `readwrite` mode.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] You open such transactions with `IDBDatabase.transaction`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The method accepts two parameters: the `storeNames` (the scope, defined as an array of object stores that you want to access) and the `mode` (`readonly` or `readwrite`) for the transaction.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The method returns a transaction object containing the `IDBIndex.objectStore` method, which you can use to access your object store.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] By default, where no mode is specified, transactions open in `readonly` mode.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] You can speed up data access by using the right scope and mode in the transaction.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you've just created a database, then you probably want to write to it.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The `transaction()` function takes two arguments (though one is optional) and returns a transaction object.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The first argument is a list of object stores that the transaction will span.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] You can pass an empty array if you want the transaction to span all object stores, but don't do it because the spec says an empty array should generate an InvalidAccessError.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you don't specify anything for the second argument, you get a read-only transaction.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Since you want to write to it here you need to pass the `"readwrite"` flag.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Now that you have a transaction you need to understand its lifetime.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Transactions are tied very closely to the event loop.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you make a transaction and return to the event loop without using it then the transaction will become inactive.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The only way to keep the transaction active is to make a request on it.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] When the request is finished you'll get a DOM event and, assuming that the request succeeded, you'll have another opportunity to extend the transaction during that callback.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you return to the event loop without extending the transaction then it will become inactive, and so on.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] As long as there are pending requests the transaction remains active.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Transaction lifetimes are really very simple but it might take a little time to get used to.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you start seeing `TRANSACTION_INACTIVE_ERR` error codes then you've messed something up.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Transactions can receive DOM events of three different types: `error`, `abort`, and `complete`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] We've talked about the way that `error` events bubble, so a transaction receives error events from any requests that are generated from it.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] A more subtle point here is that the default behavior of an error is to abort the transaction in which it occurred.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Unless you handle the error by first calling `stopPropagation()` on the error event then doing something else, the entire transaction is rolled back.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] This design forces you to think about and handle errors, but you can always add a catchall error handler to the database if fine-grained error handling is too cumbersome.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you don't handle an error event or if you call `abort()` on the transaction, then the transaction is rolled back and an `abort` event is fired on the transaction.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Otherwise, after all pending requests have completed, you'll get a `complete` event.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you're doing lots of database operations, then tracking the transaction rather than individual requests can certainly aid your sanity.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Now that you have a transaction, you'll need to get the object store from it.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Transactions only let you have an object store that you specified when creating the transaction.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The `result` of a request generated from a call to `add()` is the key of the value that was added.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] So in this case, it should equal the `ssn` property of the object that was added, since the object store uses the `ssn` property for the key path.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Note that the `add()` function requires that no object already be in the database with the same key.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you're trying to modify an existing entry, or you don't care if one exists already, you can use the `put()` function, as shown below in the Updating an entry in the database section.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Now that the database has some info in it, you can retrieve it in several ways.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] That's a lot of code for a "simple" retrieval.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Since there's only one object store, you can avoid passing a list of object stores you need in your transaction and just pass the name as a string.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Also, you're only reading from the database, so you don't need a `"readwrite"` transaction.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Calling `transaction()` with no mode specified gives you a `"readonly"` transaction.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Another subtlety here is that you don't actually save the request object to a variable.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Since the DOM event has the request as its target you can use the event to get to the `result` property.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Now we've retrieved some data, updating it and inserting it back into the IndexedDB is pretty simple.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] So here we're creating an `objectStore` and requesting a customer record out of it, identified by its ssn value (`444-44-4444`).
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] We then put the result of that request in a variable (`data`), update the `age` property of this object, then create a second request (`requestUpdate`) to put the customer record back into the `objectStore`, overwriting the previous value.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Using `get()` requires that you know which key you want to retrieve.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you want to step through all the values in your object store, then you can use a cursor.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The `openCursor()` function takes several arguments.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] First, you can limit the range of items that are retrieved by using a key range object that we'll get to in a minute.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Second, you can specify the direction that you want to iterate.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] In the above example, we're iterating over all objects in ascending order.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The success callback for cursors is a little special.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The cursor object itself is the `result` of the request (above we're using the shorthand, so it's `event.target.result`).
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Then the actual key and value can be found on the `key` and `value` properties of the cursor object.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you want to keep going, then you have to call `continue()` on the cursor.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] When you've reached the end of the data (or if there were no entries that matched your `openCursor()` request) you still get a success callback, but the `result` property is `undefined`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] There is a performance cost associated with looking at the `value` property of a cursor, because the object is created lazily.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] When you use `getAll()` for example, the browser must create all the objects at once.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you're just interested in looking at each of the keys, for instance, it is much more efficient to use a cursor than to use `getAll()`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you're trying to get an array of all the objects in an object store, though, use `getAll()`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Storing customer data using the SSN as a key is logical since the SSN uniquely identifies an individual.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] (Whether this is a good idea for privacy is a different question, and outside the scope of this article.) If you need to look up a customer by name, however, you'll need to iterate over every SSN in the database until you find the right one.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Searching in this fashion would be very slow, so instead you can use an index.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The "name" index isn't unique, so there could be more than one entry with the `name` set to `"Donna"`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] In that case you always get the one with the lowest key value.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you need to access all the entries with a given `name` you can use a cursor.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] You can open two different types of cursors on indexes.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] A normal cursor maps the index property to the object in the object store.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] A key cursor maps the index property to the key used to store the object in the object store.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The index can also be created on multiple properties, allowing to look up records using a combination of values, such as finding a person by both their name and email.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] To create a compound index, pass an array of property names as the key path when calling `createIndex`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] You can then query the index by passing an array of values in the same order.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you would like to limit the range of values you see in a cursor, you can use an `IDBKeyRange` object and pass it as the first argument to `openCursor()` or `openKeyCursor()`.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] You can make a key range that only allows a single key, or one that has a lower or upper bound, or one that has both a lower and upper bound.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The bound may be "closed" (i.e., the key range includes the given value(s)) or "open" (i.e., the key range does not include the given value(s)).
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Sometimes you may want to iterate in descending order rather than in ascending order (the default direction for all cursors).
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Since the "name" index isn't unique, there might be multiple entries where `name` is the same.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Note that such a situation cannot occur with object stores since the key must always be unique.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you wish to filter out duplicates during cursor iteration over indexes, you can pass `nextunique` (or `prevunique` if you're going backwards) as the direction parameter.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] When `nextunique` or `prevunique` is used, the entry with the lowest key is always the one returned.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Please see "IDBCursor Constants" for the valid direction arguments.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] When your web app changes in such a way that a version change is required for your database, you need to consider what happens if the user has the old version of your app open in one tab and then loads the new version of your app in another.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] When you call `open()` with a greater version than the actual version of the database, all other open databases must explicitly acknowledge the request before you can start making changes to the database (an `onblocked` event is fired until they are closed or reloaded).
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] You should also listen for `VersionError` errors to handle the situation where already opened apps may initiate code leading to a new attempt to open the database, but using an outdated version.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] IndexedDB uses the same-origin principle, which means that it ties the store to the origin of the site that creates it (typically, this is the site domain or subdomain), so it cannot be accessed by any other origin.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Third party window content (e.g., `<iframe>` content) cannot access IndexedDB if the browser is set to never accept third party cookies (see Firefox bug 1147821).
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Once all of the transactions have completed, the database connection is closed.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Finally, the `IDBDatabase` object representing the database connection receives a `close` event.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] You can use the `IDBDatabase.onclose` event handler to listen for these events, so that you know when a database is unexpectedly closed.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The behavior described above is new, and is only available as of the following browser releases: Firefox 50, Google Chrome 31 (approximately).
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Prior to these browser versions, the transactions are aborted silently, and no `close` event is fired, so there is no way to detect an unexpected database closure.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Since the user can exit the browser at any time, this means that you cannot rely upon any particular transaction to complete, and on older browsers, you don't even get told when they don't complete.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] There are several implications of this behavior.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] First, you should take care to always leave your database in a consistent state at the end of every transaction.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] For example, suppose that you are using IndexedDB to store a list of items that you allow the user to edit.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] You save the list after the edit by clearing the object store and then writing out the new list.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If you clear the object store in one transaction and write the new list in another transaction, there is a danger that the browser will close after the clear but before the write, leaving you with an empty database.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] To avoid this, you should combine the clear and the write into a single transaction.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] Second, you should never tie database transactions to unload events.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] If the unload event is triggered by the browser closing, any transactions created in the unload event handler will never complete.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] An intuitive approach to maintaining some information across browser sessions is to read it from the database when the browser (or a particular page) is opened, update it as the user interacts with the browser, and then save it to the database when the browser (or page) closes.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The database transactions will be created in the unload event handler, but because they are asynchronous they will be aborted before they can execute.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] In fact, there is no way to guarantee that IndexedDB transactions will complete, even with normal browser shutdown.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] As a workaround for this normal shutdown notification, you might track your transactions and add a `beforeunload` event to warn the user if any transactions have not yet completed at the time of unloading.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] At least with the addition of the abort notifications and `IDBDatabase.onclose`, you can know when this has happened.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] We have a complete example using the IndexedDB API.
[src:indexeddb/using-indexeddb] The example uses IndexedDB to store and retrieve publications.
